can we just send TAO directly from CEX to Subtensor network in Metamask ?

CEX have so far only integrated with the polkadot chain format of SS58, MetaMask by default uses h160. Until the CEXes figure out the can also use h160, make sure you never use your Bittensor native wallet on a CEX or you will loose the funds

1) Transfer TAO from exchanges to your SS58 wallet
2) Create/import new account into your Metamask. This is H160 account
3) Now to go https://snow-address-converter.netlify.app/ and enter your Metamask address choose the H160 as format
4) Click on GO and you see your SS58 address corresponds to your H160 Metamask wallet
5) Now copy that SS58 from site, and transfer your TAO and in few mins you will see your TAO in metamask

Note: remember to add the Subtensor EVM mainnet network to Metamask

lol me and some others who have tried deploying on mainnet brought up this issue before. a colleague of mine recently figured out what's wrong. tldr:
if you're setting your evm version to Paris when compiling your contracts you'll run into this issue. Bittensor's EVM rpc does not provide `prevrandao` value. `prevrandao` was introduced in the EVM Paris upgrade to replace `difficulty` (block difficulty).  This means that in order to wait for transaction receipt properly we need to use some version prior to Paris. My colleague tried using London in foundry and it worked fine. However after going down to London on hardhat, it still did not work but this time did not even send transaction on chain ☹️. Obviously the workaround for this if you still want to use Paris + Hardhat is to basically deploying the contracts one by one without waiting for the tx receipts but it's no great :p .

If I were to use staked TAO as a voting power I couldn't rely on the current stake, which can get easily manipulated.
Assuming bittensor attracts more user it's only a matter of time when lending/borrowing defi comes.
Then a validator could do the following in a single transaction:
1. flash borrow a lot of TAO from a lending protocol
2. stake the TAO calling add_stake on the precompile
3. cast a vote using the inflated stake <- that manipulates a voting outcome
4. unstake the TAO calling remove_stake on the precompile
5. return the borrowed amount to the lending protocol
Flash loan mechanism doesn't need collateral, hence it's easy to use to inflate the stake for a duration of  a single transaction.
